{
  "game_explanation": "Three players each start with 10 red and 10 green chips. Green chips are common-value (0.50 each). Red chips have heterogeneous private values: dog 0.30, buffalo 0.10, cat 0.40. Because players care only about their own total value, proposers will try to convert lower-value holdings into higher-value ones for themselves (e.g., buy greens by offering reds), and responders will accept only if the trade increases their own value in expectation. Uncertainty arises from (1) private asymmetries in red values (responders know only their own valuation), (2) the rule that if multiple responders accept one is chosen at random (so expected payoff is reduced under competition), and (3) future opportunity costs across the three rounds. Given valuations, buffalo (with the lowest red value) has the most to gain from buying greens by offering reds, and cat (with moderately high red value) can be a willing counterparty when offered enough red. Dog's red value is intermediate. Forecasted pattern: many small 1:1 proposals to buy a green for 1 red will be declined because they are unfavorable to responders; profitable trades for the proposer typically require offering multiple reds per green; buffalo as buyer offering 2 red for 1 green is attractive to both dog and cat, so such proposals are likely to draw multiple acceptances and be resolved by random selection. Overall expect a few mutually beneficial asymmetric exchanges (buffalo buying greens by selling multiple reds) and many declined low-margin offers.",
